Cell[TextData[{
  "\tThe enumeration scheme for the elements ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(a\_\(i, j\)\)]],
  " in (1) do not take advantage of the overwhelming number of zeros.  If the \
two subscripts were retained the computer would reserve storage for  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(n\^2\)]],
  " elements.  Since practical applications involve large values of  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(n >> 1000\)]],
  ", it is important to devise a more efficient way to label only those \
elements that will be used and conceptualize the existence of all those off \
diagonal zeros.  The idea that is often used is to call elements of the main \
diagonal ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \({d\_i}\_\(i = 1\)\%n\)]],
  ", ",
  ButtonBox["subdiagonal elements",
    ButtonData:>{
      URL[ "http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Subdiagonal.html"], None},
    ButtonStyle->"Hyperlink"],
  " ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \({a\_i}\_\(i = 1\)\%\(n - 1\)\)]],
  "  are directly below the main diagonal, and the ",
  ButtonBox["superdiagonal elements",
    ButtonData:>{
      URL[ "http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Superdiagonal.html"], None},
    ButtonStyle->"Hyperlink"],
  "  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \({c\_i}\_\(i = 1\)\%\(n - 1\)\)]],
  "  are directly above the main diagonal.  Taking advantage of the single \
subscripts on ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{\(a\_i\), 
        StyleBox[",",
          FontFamily->"Times New Roman",
          FontSize->12,
          FontWeight->"Plain",
          FontSlant->"Plain",
          FontColor->GrayLevel[0],
          FontVariations->{"Underline"->False,
          "StrikeThrough"->False}], \(d\_i\), 
        StyleBox[",",
          FontFamily->"Times New Roman",
          FontSize->12,
          FontWeight->"Plain",
          FontSlant->"Plain",
          FontColor->GrayLevel[0],
          FontVariations->{"Underline"->False,
          "StrikeThrough"->False}], \(and\ c\_i\)}]]],
  " we can reduce the storage requirement to merely ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(3  n - 2\)]],
  "  elements.  This bizarre way of looking at a tridiagonal matrix is  \n\n\
",
  StyleBox["\t",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{
        StyleBox["A",
          FontWeight->"Bold"], " ", "=", 
        RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
              {\(d\_1\), \(c\_1\), "0", "0", "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", "\[CenterEllipsis]", "0", "0", "0", 
                "0"},
              {\(a\_1\), \(d\_2\), \(c\_2\), "0", "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", "\[CenterEllipsis]", "0", "0", "0", 
                "0"},
              {"0", \(a\_2\), \(d\_3\), \(c\_3\), "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", "\[CenterEllipsis]", "0", "0", "0", 
                "0"},
              {"\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[VerticalEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[DescendingEllipsis]", 
                "\[DescendingEllipsis]", "\[DescendingEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[AscendingEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "0"},
              {"0", "0", "0", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", \(a\_\(i - 1\)\), \(d\_i\), \(c\_i\), 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", "0", "0", "0"},
              {"\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[VerticalEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[AscendingEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[DescendingEllipsis]", 
                "\[DescendingEllipsis]", "\[DescendingEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]", "\[VerticalEllipsis]", 
                "\[VerticalEllipsis]"},
              {"0", "0", "0", "0", "\[CenterEllipsis]", "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", \(a\_\(n - 3\)\), \(d\_\(n - 
                      2\)\), \(c\_\(n - 2\)\), "0"},
              {"0", "0", "0", "0", "\[CenterEllipsis]", "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "0", \(a\_\(n - 2\)\), \(d\_\(n - 1\)\), \(c\_\(n - 1\)\)},
              {"0", "0", "0", "0", "\[CenterEllipsis]", "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "\[CenterEllipsis]", 
                "0", \(\(\ \)\(0\)\), \(a\_\(n - 1\)\), \(d\_n\)}
              }], ")"}]}]]],
  ".\n\nObserve that ",
  StyleBox["A",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " does not have the usual alphabetical connection with its new elements \
named  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{\(a\_i\), 
        StyleBox[",",
          FontFamily->"Times New Roman",
          FontSize->12,
          FontWeight->"Plain",
          FontSlant->"Plain",
          FontColor->GrayLevel[0],
          FontVariations->{"Underline"->False,
          "StrikeThrough"->False}], \(d\_i\), 
        StyleBox[",",
          FontFamily->"Times New Roman",
          FontSize->12,
          FontWeight->"Plain",
          FontSlant->"Plain",
          FontColor->GrayLevel[0],
          FontVariations->{"Underline"->False,
          "StrikeThrough"->False}], \(and\ c\_i\)}]]],
  ", and that the length of the subdiagonal and superdiagonal is ",
  StyleBox["n-1",
    FontFamily->"Courier New"],
  "."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
  StyleBox["Definition (",
